Posts.Content: The day after my house and car were engulfed in a tidal surge I suffered acute urinary retention, which required the fitting of an emergency catheter. The catheter was removed on 6 January after but it had to be re-inserted on 8 January as I went into acute urinary retention again. I still have the catheter today. Last week I had a PSA test which gave a reading of 285. I have not had any infection for three weeks so, I guess, the abnormally high reading cannot be explained by a UTI. With such a high reading does anyone know the likelihood that the PSA reading is due to cancer? The consultant suggested that it was abnormally high and could not be explained by BPH, UTI or any other cause, other than prostate cancer.
Posts.Title: High PSA Reading of 285

Posts.Content: Originally Posted by Walnut Oops, too late. Good luck with the results. Mine were back the next day. Waiting is hard so I hope they call you tomorrow. Hi Walnut. You have an interesting choice of name given that a normal prostate is about the size of a walnut.
Posts.Title: High PSA Reading of 285

Posts.Content: Originally Posted by lancepeace Welcome. I am not a doctor but would guess there is a good chance the high PSA might be from prostate cancer. An outpatient biopsy taking tiny samples of the prostate would be the main test to diagnose. Do you know the size of the prostate? Was there a nodule on the prostate? Do you know your prior PSA test results? What is your age? If it is prostate cancer, many grow fairly slowly. Treatment is often helpful. Recomment you go ahead and see a urologist about a biopsy. Good luck. Apparently, the prostate is very enlarged, smooth (no nodules) and firm (rather than hard). I did have a biopsy today and they took a total of 11 samples. Procedure was painless and virtually no bleeding. I am 62 and never had a PSA test done before. I have had difficulty urinating in the morning (sometimes) for the past two years but after walking around for a few minutes I could pee normally. That was really my only symptom until I had acute urinary retention. nearly 8 weeks ago.

Posts.Content: Originally Posted by Walnut It's a mystery. How does the stress of that damage to your home figure into the urinary retention??????? Apparently stress hit you very hard. How does that figure into the high PSA??? Here's a fact. One PSA doesn't prove anything. I would say proceed with stress counseling, second and third opinions and get a state of the art MRI at a highly rated facility. You can always get a biopsy if the MRI shows something suspicious. I did wonder if anyone has also experienced acute urinary retention following stress. It is certainly mentioned as a cause here: http://www.rightdiagnosis.com/artic/...orks_niddk.htm. But I don't know if stress can lead to a high PSA as I cannot find anything on the internet about it and I forgot to ask my consultant that question. Sorry, I forgot to mention that I had a biopsy today.

Posts.Content: HighlanderCFH: Thank you for your kind comments. I think you are probably right that a PSA of 286 cannot be explained by BPH alone. My consultant certainly did not think it could be due to BPH. He could only suggest cancer as the cause. I did wonder if it could be due to Polio I suffered as a child. I do know that people who have had Polio have a high Creatine Kinase level - which is an enzyme. PSA is also an enzyme, but I could be clutching at straws here.
